    <body>
        <div xml:id="AN21-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN21">
            <lg type="edition"><l>maṉaivaḷar nocci mauval <choice><seg>vāṉmukait</seg><seg>vāṇmukait</seg></choice></l>
<l>tuṇainirait taṉṉa mā<supplied>vī</supplied>ḻ veṇpa</l>
<l>lavvayiṟ ṟakaṉṟa valkuṟ <choice><seg>ṟaiiyat</seg><seg>ṟaiit</seg></choice></l>
<l>tāḻmeṉ kūntaṟ <choice><seg>ṟaṭameṉ</seg><seg>ṟakaimeṉ</seg></choice> paṇaittōṇ</l>
<l>maṭantai māṇalam <choice><seg>pacappac</seg><seg>pulampac</seg></choice> cēynāṭṭuc</l>
<l><choice><seg>cellala</seg><seg>cella</seg></choice> <choice><seg>meṉṟiyāṉ</seg><seg>leṉṟiyāṉ</seg></choice> collavu mollāy</l>
<l>viṉainayan tamaintaṉai yāyiṉ maṉai<supplied>nakap</supplied></l>
<l><supplied>pa</supplied>lvēṟu veṟukkai tarukam vallē</l>
<l>yeḻuviṉi <choice><seg>vāḻiya</seg><seg>vāḻiye</seg></choice> <choice><seg>neñcē</seg><seg>ṉeñcē</seg></choice> puriyi<supplied>ṇa</supplied>r</l>
<l>mellavi ḻañciṉai pulampa vallōṉ</l>
<l>kōṭaṟai kompiṉ vīyukat tīṇṭi</l>
<l>marāa <choice><seg>malainta</seg><seg>malaitta</seg></choice> maṇavāyt teṉṟal</l>
<l>curañceṉ maḷḷar curiyaṟ ṟūṟṟu</l>
<l>meṉṟūḻ niṉṟa puṉṟalai vaippiṟ</l>
<l>paruntiḷaip paṭūum pāṟutalai yōmai</l>
<l>yiruṅkal viṭarakat tīṉṟiḷaip paṭṭa</l>
<l>meṉpuṉiṟ ṟampiṇavup pacitteṉap paiṅkaṭ</l>
<l><choice><seg>cennā</seg><seg>ceṉṉā</seg></choice> <choice><seg>yēṟṟai</seg><seg>yēṟṟaik</seg></choice> kēḻa ṟākka</l>
<l>viriyaṟ piṇava ṟīṇṭaliṟ <choice><seg>parīic</seg><seg>paṟīic</seg></choice></l>
<l>ceṅkā yutirnta paiṅkulai yīntiṉ</l>
<l>paraṉmaṭ cuvara muraṇila muṭaitta</l>
<l><choice><seg>vāyak</seg><seg>valvāyk</seg></choice> kaṇiccik kūḻār kōvala</l>
<l>rūṟā <choice><seg>tīṭṭa</seg><seg>tiṭṭa</seg></choice> vuvalaik kūval</l>
<l>veṇkōṭu nayanta vaṉpil kāṉava</l>
<l>rikaḻntiyaṅ kiyavi ṉakaḻnta ku<supplied>ḻi</supplied>cet</l>
<l>tiruṅkaḷiṟ ṟiṉanirai tūrkkum</l>
<l>peruṅka lattam vilaṅkiya kāṭē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Even though I said : <choice><seg>“we won’t </seg><seg>“don’t </seg></choice> go</l>
<l rend="indent">	to distant lands so that the glorious beauty of [our] girl <choice><seg>fades,</seg><seg>will be lonely,</seg></choice> </l>
<l rend="indent">	with <choice><seg>broad </seg><seg>befitting </seg></choice> soft bamboo shoulders, with soft tresses that hang <choice><seg>down</seg><seg>down,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	so as to join </seg><seg>	tying in </seg></choice> [her] wide hips, with a pretty belly,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with big, desirable white teeth as if put in a row as companions,</l>
<l><choice><seg>	pure </seg><seg>	generous </seg></choice> buds of wild jasmine, by the chaste tree growing near the house<note place="foot">The relation of line 1 to the rest of the description is unclear.  Even if we think of jasmine buds as a standard simile for teeth, the relation to nocci remains unexplained, unless we simply take it as the tree the jasmine creeper uses as a prop (an assumption that seems to be supported by AN 23.11f.: nocci ūḻvaṉa malarum | mavval, there too without explicit mark of the relation).  The old commentary confirms the bud-tooth relation, since it glosses mā in line 2 by vaṇṭu, “bee”, suggesting for mā vīḻ the meaning “desired by bees”.</note>”,</l>
<l rend="indent6">						you did not agree.</l>
<l>If you are set in longing for work, let us bring</l>
<l>many different goods so that the house smiles, quickly</l>
<l><choice><seg>rise now, oh </seg><seg>rise now, oh my </seg></choice> heart,</l>
<l>– for the wilderness<note place="foot">The second possible link for the pūṭṭuvil would be cēynāṭṭu: the distant land that is a wilderness.</note> where roads are blocked with big stones,</l>
<l>where the herd of large elephant bulls thoughtfully</l>
<l>fill up the pits that are dug on the ways negligently walked by</l>
<l rend="indent">	loveless forest men who long for white tusks,<note place="foot">The syntactic link for kūval at the end of line 23 is in no way morphologically marked and seeing kōvalar and kāṉavar in apposition is not very satisfactory from the point of view of content.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	by wells [covered] with dried leaves <choice><seg>so that [water] accumulates without </seg><seg>placed without [water] </seg></choice> oozing out,</l>
<l rend="indent">	cowherds full of food with mouthy pick-axes</l>
<l rend="indent">	that broke the hostile ground into walls of pebble [and] earth,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with date palms in fresh bunches that shed red unripe fruit<note place="foot">The only possible way of linking up the absolutive parīi (l. 19) with what follows is to take it as dependend on kūḻ ār: the cowherds are full of food, that is, the pulp of the date fruits after they managed to chase away the female pig who was interested in the same. This, then, can be loosely related to the infinitive clause ending in tākka (l. 18).</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	after having <choice><seg>made run because they gripped [them] </seg><seg>plucked out by gripping </seg></choice> the female pigs that retreat</l>
<l rend="indent">	while the hog is attacked by the male of the <choice><seg>red </seg><seg>roaming </seg></choice> dog with green eyes,</l>
<l rend="indent">	because of the hunger of [its] pretty bitch, with a soft newly-born one,</l>
<l rend="indent">	that sank down in exhaustion after giving birth inside a cleft in the big stones</l>
<l rend="indent">	near toothbrush trees with dishevelled tops,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where kites sink down in exhaustion,</l>
<l>in a region of empty spots on which the sun stood,<note place="foot">Also the clause headed by vaippiṉ seems loosely connected at best.  One fights with the impression of being faced with the fragments of two to three different desert poems.</note></l>
<l>where the hair of warriors going through the desert is tousled</l>
<l>by the south wind, superior by the fragrance that was <choice><seg>put on </seg><seg>opposed </seg></choice> by Kadamba trees,</l>
<l>gripping, for the blossom to be shed, [their] twigs that beat the branches,</l>
<l rend="indent">	by the strong one,<note place="foot">The only possibility to integrate vallōṉ into the syntagma seems to be to take it in apposition to teṉṟal, thus personifiying the wind.</note></l>
<l>so that the opening pretty branches soft with twisted clusters become lonely.</l></lg>
        </div>
